@node 08562.002
Subject: Re: Some general questions.
From: Hans-Joerg Frieden <Hans-JoergF@hyperion-software.de>
Date: Mon, 11 Jun 2001 16:28:09 +0200

Hi!

On Monday 11 June 2001 15:33, Michal Wozniak wrote:

> 1:
>   I have read thet on modern 3dchips state changes are quite slow. Some
> suggested  to draw all faces with same surface in one loop, change
>  state and draw other faces.  Is it neccesary on Permedia? And will
>   it cause a speed decrease on Voodoo?

Rendering everything with the same texture at one go is the preferred method. 
If you can manage, sort your polies by texture/surface and render them at one 
go. The Voodoo will not slow down on this, quite the contrary - all chips 
will benefit from that due to the fact that the texture uploads will be 
minimized. 

The problem with state changes is that there might be a lot of registers 
affected that need their contents re-evaluated. This is a bit different from 
the texture stuff. Warp3D however tries to miniize this by comparing new and 
old state values and registers and only updating if they are really in need 
of updating.

>  2: If answer for 1 is: "Yes they are slow".
>     Are context states remembered by W3D, so when setting it to the same
> state  doesn't mean sending a message to the hardware? Or I have
>  to check it for myself?

No, usually you just use W3D_SetState, and the value is only changed if it is 
different.

>  3: If I would loke to draw transparent faces with z buffering, do I have
> to draw them after all nontransparent faces? I think Yes, but maybe there
> is another method.

No, if you need transparency you will most likely want to disable Z buffer 
update (you will need ZBuffer tests enabled), and draw the transparent faces 
back-to-front, otherwise things will look wrong. The order in which you draw 
transparent faces will determine the outcome.

>  4: When drawing with W3D_SYNCHRON (or something like that) how much time
> do I have for CPU while HW is doing it's job? I mean what can I do in this
> time.

Don't enable Synchron. If you enable this, Warp3D will wait for the hardware 
to become idle after every drawing command, and that will waste any amount of 
parallelism you have. Keep it disabled, and use W3D_WaitIdle after you have 
drawn the entire frame, or want to do anything major.

>  5: Does Permedia support stencil buffer? I mean ,can I set a stencil to
>  for example 1 when a pixel of drawn face is visible?

It does, but the driver doesn't. The Permedia2 stencil buffer is only one bit 
deep, and hence practically unsusable. The Voodoo 3 doesn't support any 
stencil buffer. You can use the Z buffer as a limited stencil buffer 
replacement.

