You don't need to depth sort the polygons, just put them into a list stored 
with each texture (that's what's meant with "sorting by texture"). Something 
like this:

class Texture
{
public:
	W3D_Texture *m_pTexture;
	std::list<Polygon> m_PolyList;
}

And later add the polygons to be rendered with that texture to the 
appropriate textures m_PolyList. When rendering, you'd first set the texture 
on the appropriate triangle structure, and walk the list to render all of the 
polygons in it.
You can also have seperate lists for different states and texture 
environments, like MODULATE and REPLACE, or depth buffering, this might safe 
you some state changes...

