@node 08567.001
Subject: Warp3D developer archive
From: Thomas Frieden <ThomasF@hyperion-software.de>
Date: Sat, 16 Jun 2001 12:30:24 +0200

Hi,

I've uploaded the Warp3D developer archive to Aminet, so it should pop up 
there any time now.

For the developers here, here's what's new in V4:
The most prominent new feature are of course the vertex arrays. If you know 
OpenGL's array functionality, you know what it's about. It's the possibility 
to draw a huge amount of triangles in one go. Like in OpenGL, the arrays come 
in two flavors:
W3D_DrawArray draws the current array in the order the vertices appear in the 
array, i.e. it always starts at the beginning, and draws a certain amount of 
array elements. The type of pimitive is given with the call itself 
(currently, seperate triangles, triangle strips, and fans are supported).
W3D_DrawElements is the same as OpenGL's glDrawElements: The actual vertices 
are indexed by another array.

The current arrays have to be set before calling the drawing operations, by 
calling W3D_VertexPointer (for x,y,z geometry), W3D_ColorPointer (for color), 
and W3D_TexCoordPointer (for texture coordinates, including u,v, and w).
The layout of the data is variable, and like in OpenGL, the stride (i.e. the 
amount of space between consecutive array elements) can be given for each 
individual array. 

The array functions do not take a texture pointer directly. To use a texture 
with these functions, it has to be bound. This introduces the concept of a 
current texture, which will currently only be used for the arrays (the 
single-primitive functions will still use the texture in the appropriate 
structure, for backwards compatibility). 
The function W3D_BindTexture is used for that. Note that W3D_BindTexture, as 
well as W3D_TexCoordPointer, already include a parameter to choose the 
texturing unit. Currently, everything else but 0 gives an error, but the next 
release will allow more than one texturing unit for hardware that supports 
multi texturing, adding a function to select the color operation between 
texture stages.

V4 also introduces hardware assisted backface culling. There's a new 
function, W3D_SetFrontFace, which will tell Warp3D what's to be considered 
front facing (W3D_CW for clockwise, W3D_CCW for counter clockwise). This is 
enabled or disabled by W3D_SetState with W3D_CULL_FACE.

Hopefully, this message can serve as a general guideline for V4. I didn't 
have the time to update the developer documentation, the file 
docs/Warp3D.guide contains the autodocs for all functions, though, including 
the new one. 

If you have question concerning the new (or old) functions, do not hesitate 
to contact me.

Regards,
-- 
 Thomas Frieden
 Senior Developer, Hyperion Entertainment
